---
import Layout from "../../layouts/Layout.astro";
import ProsConsList from "../../components/ProsConsList.astro";
import AffiliateButton from "../../components/AffiliateButton.astro";

const title = "Cheap Meal Prep Ideas for College Students Bulking (Under $50/Week)";
const description =
  "Build muscle without going broke. Here's exactly how to meal prep a full week of high-protein bulking meals for under $50 as a college student.";
const pubDate = "2026-04-15";
const slug = "cheap-meal-prep-college-students-bulking";

const containersUrl = "https://www.amazon.com/s?k=meal+prep+containers+set&tag=dveverka-20";
const scaleUrl = "https://www.amazon.com/s?k=food+kitchen+scale&tag=dveverka-20";
const riceCookerUrl = "https://www.amazon.com/s?k=budget+rice+cooker&tag=dveverka-20";

const pros = [
  "Cuts food cost dramatically — eating the same prepped meals is 60–70% cheaper than buying food daily",
  "Removes decision fatigue — no figuring out what to eat when you're tired and hungry",
  "Hitting a calorie surplus consistently becomes mechanical instead of a daily struggle",
  "Macro tracking becomes simple when the same meals repeat with known numbers",
  "Two hours on Sunday buys you a full week of meals that require zero thought",
];

const cons = [
  "Eating the same meals five days in a row requires tolerance for repetition",
  "Requires upfront equipment investment (containers, a food scale) that not everyone has",
  "A bad prep session — overcooked chicken, underseasoned rice — affects every meal that week",
];

const groceryList = [
  { item: "Chicken thighs (3 lbs)",         store: "Walmart/Aldi", price: "$5–7" },
  { item: "Ground beef 80/20 (2 lbs)",       store: "Walmart/Aldi", price: "$7–9" },
  { item: "Eggs (18-count)",                 store: "Walmart/Aldi", price: "$3–4" },
  { item: "White rice (5 lb bag)",           store: "Walmart/Aldi", price: "$3–4" },
  { item: "Sweet potatoes (3 lbs)",          store: "Walmart/Aldi", price: "$3–4" },
  { item: "Kodiak Waffles (1 box)",          store: "Walmart",      price: "$5–6" },
  { item: "Premier Protein shakes (4-pack)", store: "Walmart",      price: "$7–8" },
  { item: "Bananas (bunch)",                 store: "Walmart/Aldi", price: "$1–2" },
  { item: "Peanut butter (16 oz)",           store: "Walmart/Aldi", price: "$3–4" },
  { item: "Cottage cheese (24 oz)",          store: "Walmart/Aldi", price: "$3–4" },
  { item: "Olive oil, salt, garlic powder",  store: "Pantry",       price: "$0" },
];
---

<Layout {title} {description} canonicalUrl={`/guides/${slug}`}>
  <article class="review">
    <header>
      <h1>{title}</h1>
      <p class="meta">
        Published: <time datetime={pubDate}>{pubDate}</time>
      </p>
    </header>

    <section>
      <p>
        Eating enough to actually bulk on a college budget sounds impossible until you do
        the math. Three thousand calories a day from dining hall food runs $15–20 per day.
        Three thousand calories from a Sunday meal prep runs $7. That gap — over a semester —
        is the difference between a real bulk and spinning your wheels because you're
        undereating four days out of seven.
      </p>
      <p>
        This guide covers exactly what to buy, what to cook, how to prep it in two hours,
        and how to hit 3,000–3,500 calories with 180g+ of protein every day for under $50
        a week. No complicated recipes, no exotic ingredients, nothing that requires a
        full kitchen or three hours on a Sunday afternoon.
      </p>
    </section>

    <!-- Calorie needs -->
    <section>
      <h2>How Many Calories Do You Actually Need to Bulk?</h2>
      <p>
        A bulk requires a calorie surplus — eating more than your body burns so it has the
        raw materials to build muscle. The challenge is finding a surplus that's big enough
        to drive growth but small enough that you're not gaining more fat than muscle.
      </p>
      <p>
        A simple starting point: <strong>multiply your bodyweight in pounds by 16–18</strong>.
        A 170 lb college student needs roughly 2,720–3,060 calories per day to be in a
        meaningful surplus. Aim for the lower end if you tend to gain fat easily; the higher
        end if you have a fast metabolism and struggle to gain weight at all.
      </p>
      <p>
        For protein, target <strong>0.8–1g per pound of bodyweight</strong>. At 170 lbs
        that's 136–170g of protein per day. The meal plan below hits 180g+ daily, which
        gives you a buffer and makes the math forgiving even if one meal is smaller than
        planned.
      </p>
      <p>
        These are starting numbers, not commandments. If you're not gaining weight after
        two weeks, add 200 calories. If you're gaining faster than 1 lb per week and noticing
        more fat than muscle, pull back 200. Adjust based on what the scale actually does.
      </p>
    </section>

    <!-- Weekly meal plan -->
    <section>
      <h2>Full Weekly Meal Plan (~3,200 Calories, 185g Protein)</h2>
      <p>
        The same structure repeats Monday through Friday. Weekends you're on your own — this
        isn't a religion, it's a system. Five consistent days beats seven inconsistent ones.
      </p>

      <div class="meal-block">
        <h3>Breakfast — Eggs + Kodiak Waffles</h3>
        <div class="meal-macros">
          <span>~600 cal</span>
          <span>~40g protein</span>
          <span>~55g carbs</span>
        </div>
        <p>
          Two Kodiak waffles (toasted from frozen) plus three scrambled eggs. The waffles give
          you 24g of whole grain protein and slow carbs; the eggs add 18g more and healthy fat.
          This takes four minutes and requires only a toaster and a pan. Make the eggs fresh each
          morning — they don't prep well — but the waffles are already done. Add a banana for an
          extra 100 calories and 27g of carbs if you're training in the morning.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="meal-block">
        <h3>Lunch — Ground Beef Rice Bowls</h3>
        <div class="meal-macros">
          <span>~850 cal</span>
          <span>~55g protein</span>
          <span>~80g carbs</span>
        </div>
        <p>
          1 cup cooked white rice, 5 oz cooked 80/20 ground beef, seasoned with garlic powder,
          salt, and a little olive oil. That's it. Ground beef is one of the most calorie-dense
          and protein-dense cheap meats available, and 80/20 hits harder on a bulk than leaner
          ground beef because the fat content boosts the calorie total without requiring you to
          eat more volume. Pre-cook a full 2 lb batch on Sunday, portion into containers, and
          it keeps in the fridge all week.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="meal-block">
        <h3>Dinner — Chicken Thighs + Sweet Potato</h3>
        <div class="meal-macros">
          <span>~750 cal</span>
          <span>~55g protein</span>
          <span>~55g carbs</span>
        </div>
        <p>
          Two bone-in or boneless chicken thighs (baked or air-fried), one medium sweet potato
          (baked). Chicken thighs are cheaper than breasts, more forgiving to cook, and carry
          more fat — which helps the calorie count without requiring huge portion sizes. Season
          with whatever you have: garlic powder, paprika, salt. Prep all thighs and sweet potatoes
          on Sunday, portion into containers, and reheat in the microwave. This is the dinner
          that makes the week work.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="meal-block">
        <h3>Snacks — Premier Protein + Banana + Peanut Butter</h3>
        <div class="meal-macros">
          <span>~550 cal</span>
          <span>~38g protein</span>
          <span>~45g carbs</span>
        </div>
        <p>
          One Premier Protein shake (30g protein, 160 cal), one banana (~100 cal), and two
          tablespoons of peanut butter (~190 cal, 8g protein). This snack combination hits
          almost 550 calories and nearly 40g of protein with zero preparation. Keep shakes in
          your fridge, peanut butter in your bag, and bananas on your desk. It's the fallback
          for when you're between classes and need calories fast.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="meal-totals">
        <h3>Daily Totals</h3>
        <div class="totals-grid">
          <div><span class="total-label">Calories</span><span class="total-value">~3,200</span></div>
          <div><span class="total-label">Protein</span><span class="total-value">~188g</span></div>
          <div><span class="total-label">Carbs</span><span class="total-value">~235g</span></div>
          <div><span class="total-label">Cost/Day</span><span class="total-value">~$7</span></div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- Grocery list -->
    <section>
      <h2>Full Grocery List With Estimated Costs</h2>
      <p>
        Prices are estimates based on Walmart and Aldi. Aldi will usually be cheaper on
        produce, eggs, and dairy. Walmart wins on brand-name items like Kodiak and Premier
        Protein.
      </p>
      <div class="table-wrap">
        <table class="grocery-table">
          <thead>
            <tr>
              <th>Item</th>
              <th>Where to Buy</th>
              <th>Est. Cost</th>
            </tr>
          </thead>
          <tbody>
            {groceryList.map((row) => (
              <tr>
                <td>{row.item}</td>
                <td class="store">{row.store}</td>
                <td class="price">{row.price}</td>
              </tr>
            ))}
            <tr class="total-row">
              <td><strong>Weekly Total</strong></td>
              <td></td>
              <td class="price"><strong>~$40–52</strong></td>
            </tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </div>
      <p>
        The rice, peanut butter, and olive oil last multiple weeks, so your second and third
        week of this plan will cost less. The protein shakes are the most expensive line item
        — buying a 12-pack instead of a 4-pack drops the per-shake cost significantly.
      </p>
    </section>

    <!-- Sunday prep routine -->
    <section>
      <h2>Step-by-Step Sunday Prep Routine (2 Hours)</h2>
      <p>
        The goal is to do everything in parallel so no step is waiting on another. Start to
        finish in under two hours with this sequence.
      </p>

      <div class="prep-step">
        <span class="step-num">0:00</span>
        <div>
          <strong>Start the rice cooker and preheat the oven to 400°F.</strong> Put 3 cups
          of dry rice in the cooker with the appropriate water. Season and arrange chicken
          thighs on a baking sheet. Put sweet potatoes directly on the oven rack.
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="prep-step">
        <span class="step-num">0:10</span>
        <div>
          <strong>Chicken thighs and sweet potatoes go in the oven.</strong> Chicken thighs
          take 35–40 minutes at 400°F. Sweet potatoes take 45–60 minutes depending on size.
          Set a timer and walk away.
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="prep-step">
        <span class="step-num">0:15</span>
        <div>
          <strong>Brown the ground beef on the stove.</strong> Cook all 2 lbs in a large pan
          over medium-high heat. Season with garlic powder and salt. Break it up, cook through,
          drain excess fat. This takes about 15 minutes.
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="prep-step">
        <span class="step-num">0:35</span>
        <div>
          <strong>Ground beef is done. Rice should be finishing soon.</strong> Let the beef
          cool on the stove. Check the rice cooker — if it's done, let it rest for 5 minutes
          before portioning.
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="prep-step">
        <span class="step-num">0:50</span>
        <div>
          <strong>Pull chicken and sweet potatoes from the oven.</strong> Verify chicken
          reaches 165°F internal temp. Let everything rest for 5–10 minutes before
          portioning — hot food in sealed containers builds condensation and turns mushy faster.
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="prep-step">
        <span class="step-num">1:05</span>
        <div>
          <strong>Portion everything into containers.</strong> Five lunch containers: 1 cup
          rice + 5 oz ground beef each. Five dinner containers: 2 chicken thighs + 1 sweet
          potato each. Label with the day if it helps. Stack in the fridge.
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="prep-step">
        <span class="step-num">1:30</span>
        <div>
          <strong>Done.</strong> Wash the pan and baking sheet while containers cool before
          sealing. The entire week of lunches and dinners is in the fridge. Breakfast is a
          toaster and a pan each morning. Snacks require no prep at all.
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- Protein sources ranked -->
    <section>
      <h2>Best Cheap Protein Sources Ranked by Cost Per Gram</h2>
      <p>
        Not all cheap protein is equal. Here's the honest ranking so you can make smart
        substitutions if something is out of stock or on sale.
      </p>
      <div class="table-wrap">
        <table class="protein-table">
          <thead>
            <tr>
              <th>Source</th>
              <th>Protein per serving</th>
              <th>Approx. cost</th>
              <th>Cost per 10g protein</th>
            </tr>
          </thead>
          <tbody>
            <tr>
              <td>Eggs (2 large)</td>
              <td>12g</td>
              <td>~$0.35</td>
              <td class="cost-best">~$0.29</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td>Canned tuna (5 oz)</td>
              <td>25g</td>
              <td>~$1.00</td>
              <td class="cost-best">~$0.40</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td>Chicken thighs (4 oz cooked)</td>
              <td>28g</td>
              <td>~$1.00</td>
              <td class="cost-good">~$0.36</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td>Ground beef 80/20 (4 oz cooked)</td>
              <td>22g</td>
              <td>~$1.20</td>
              <td class="cost-good">~$0.55</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td>Cottage cheese (½ cup)</td>
              <td>14g</td>
              <td>~$0.60</td>
              <td class="cost-good">~$0.43</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td>Chicken breast (4 oz cooked)</td>
              <td>35g</td>
              <td>~$1.75</td>
              <td class="cost-mid">~$0.50</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td>Greek yogurt (6 oz)</td>
              <td>17g</td>
              <td>~$1.25</td>
              <td class="cost-mid">~$0.74</td>
            </tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </div>
      <p>
        Eggs and canned tuna are the best values in the entire food supply at under $0.40
        per 10g of protein. Ground beef earns its place on a bulk specifically because the
        fat content adds calories efficiently — you get more total energy per dollar than
        leaner sources. Chicken breast is actually worse value than thighs once you account
        for the higher price and lower calorie density.
      </p>
    </section>

    <!-- Pros & Cons -->
    <section>
      <h2>Meal Prepping for a Bulk: Pros & Cons</h2>
      <ProsConsList pros={pros} cons={cons} />
    </section>

    <!-- Who should do this -->
    <section>
      <h2>Who Should Do This</h2>
      <ul>
        <li>
          <strong>Students who are consistently undereating their bulk targets.</strong>
          If you end most days 300–500 calories short because you ran out of time or didn't
          have food available, this system solves that problem completely.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Anyone trying to gain muscle on a tight grocery budget.</strong> Under $50
          a week for 3,200 calories and 185g of protein is difficult to beat from any
          other food source.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Students with access to even a minimal kitchen.</strong> An oven, a stove,
          a rice cooker — that's the equipment list. If you have those, you can run this plan.
        </li>
      </ul>
    </section>

    <!-- Who should skip -->
    <section>
      <h2>Who Should Skip (or Modify) This</h2>
      <ul>
        <li>
          <strong>Students with no kitchen access at all.</strong> If your dorm situation
          genuinely has no stove or oven, this plan doesn't work. Focus instead on high-calorie
          ready-to-eat foods: nut butters, protein shakes, whole milk, trail mix, and whatever
          the dining hall offers.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>People who find food repetition genuinely unsustainable.</strong> Eating
          the same lunch every day isn't for everyone. If it's going to make you miserable
          and abandon the plan by Wednesday, rotate two or three different proteins week to
          week — ground beef one week, canned tuna the next, chicken thighs the third.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Students already eating enough to bulk consistently.</strong> If you're
          hitting your calories and protein targets without meal prep, the system is already
          working. Don't add complexity to a process that isn't broken.
        </li>
      </ul>
    </section>

    <!-- Final Verdict -->
    <section>
      <h2>Final Verdict</h2>
      <p>
        The hardest part of bulking as a college student isn't the training — it's the
        eating. Getting 3,000+ calories in on a day with 8 AM classes, afternoon labs, and
        no money for takeout requires a system, not willpower. This is the system.
      </p>
      <p>
        Two hours on Sunday, under $50 at Walmart or Aldi, and you have every lunch and dinner
        for the week already portioned and ready to microwave. Add a banana and peanut butter
        at your desk, Kodiak waffles and eggs in the morning, a Premier Protein shake between
        classes, and hitting your bulk targets becomes something you do automatically instead
        of something you have to think about every day.
      </p>
      <p>
        Get the containers first. That's the one purchase that makes the system work — food
        with nowhere to go doesn't get prepped.
      </p>
      <AffiliateButton
        href={containersUrl}
        label="Buy Meal Prep Containers on Amazon"
      />
      <div class="secondary-ctas">
        <a href={scaleUrl} target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer sponsored" class="secondary-link">
          Food Scale →
        </a>
        <a href={riceCookerUrl} target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer sponsored" class="secondary-link">
          Budget Rice Cooker →
        </a>
      </div>
      <p class="disclosure">
        <small>As an Amazon Associate I earn from qualifying purchases.</small>
      </p>
    </section>
  </article>
</Layout>

<style>
  .review {
    max-width: 740px;
    margin: 0 auto;
    padding: 2rem 1.25rem 4rem;
  }

  h1 {
    font-size: clamp(1.5rem, 4vw, 2.25rem);
    line-height: 1.25;
    margin-bottom: 0.5rem;
  }

  h2 {
    font-size: 1.35rem;
    margin: 2.5rem 0 0.75rem;
    color: #0f172a;
  }

  h3 {
    font-size: 1.05rem;
    margin: 1.5rem 0 0.4rem;
    color: #1e293b;
  }

  p {
    line-height: 1.75;
    margin: 0.75rem 0;
    color: #334155;
  }

  ul {
    padding-left: 1.25rem;
    line-height: 1.75;
    color: #334155;
  }

  li {
    margin-bottom: 0.5rem;
  }

  .meta {
    font-size: 0.875rem;
    color: #64748b;
    margin-bottom: 1.5rem;
  }

  /* Meal blocks */
  .meal-block {
    border-left: 3px solid #e2e8f0;
    padding: 0.5rem 0 0.5rem 1.25rem;
    margin: 1.5rem 0;
  }

  .meal-block h3 {
    margin-top: 0;
  }

  .meal-macros {
    display: flex;
    gap: 1rem;
    flex-wrap: wrap;
    margin: 0.25rem 0 0.5rem;
  }

  .meal-macros span {
    font-size: 0.78rem;
    font-weight: 700;
    color: #fff;
    background: #0f172a;
    padding: 0.15rem 0.5rem;
    border-radius: 0.25rem;
  }

  /* Daily totals */
  .meal-totals {
    background: #f8fafc;
    border: 1px solid #e2e8f0;
    border-radius: 0.5rem;
    padding: 1.25rem;
    margin-top: 2rem;
  }

  .meal-totals h3 {
    margin-top: 0;
    font-size: 0.9rem;
    text-transform: uppercase;
    letter-spacing: 0.05em;
    color: #64748b;
  }

  .totals-grid {
    display: flex;
    gap: 2rem;
    flex-wrap: wrap;
  }

  .total-label {
    display: block;
    font-size: 0.72rem;
    text-transform: uppercase;
    letter-spacing: 0.06em;
    color: #94a3b8;
    font-weight: 600;
  }

  .total-value {
    display: block;
    font-size: 1.25rem;
    font-weight: 800;
    color: #0f172a;
  }

  /* Tables */
  .table-wrap {
    overflow-x: auto;
    margin: 1rem 0;
  }

  .grocery-table,
  .protein-table {
    width: 100%;
    border-collapse: collapse;
    font-size: 0.875rem;
    min-width: 380px;
  }

  th {
    text-align: left;
    padding: 0.5rem 0.75rem;
    border-bottom: 2px solid #e2e8f0;
    font-size: 0.75rem;
    text-transform: uppercase;
    letter-spacing: 0.05em;
    color: #64748b;
    white-space: nowrap;
  }

  td {
    padding: 0.55rem 0.75rem;
    border-bottom: 1px solid #f1f5f9;
    color: #334155;
  }

  .store {
    color: #64748b;
    font-size: 0.82rem;
  }

  .price {
    font-weight: 700;
    color: #0f172a;
    white-space: nowrap;
  }

  .total-row td {
    border-top: 2px solid #e2e8f0;
    border-bottom: none;
    padding-top: 0.75rem;
  }

  .cost-best { font-weight: 700; color: #15803d; }
  .cost-good { font-weight: 700; color: #0891b2; }
  .cost-mid  { font-weight: 600; color: #64748b; }

  /* Prep steps */
  .prep-step {
    display: flex;
    gap: 1rem;
    align-items: flex-start;
    padding: 0.75rem 0;
    border-bottom: 1px solid #f1f5f9;
    font-size: 0.9rem;
    color: #334155;
    line-height: 1.6;
  }

  .step-num {
    flex-shrink: 0;
    font-size: 0.75rem;
    font-weight: 800;
    color: #f97316;
    background: #fff7ed;
    padding: 0.15rem 0.4rem;
    border-radius: 0.25rem;
    min-width: 2.75rem;
    text-align: center;
    margin-top: 0.1rem;
  }

  /* Secondary CTAs */
  .secondary-ctas {
    display: flex;
    gap: 1.25rem;
    margin: 0.75rem 0 0.25rem;
    flex-wrap: wrap;
  }

  .secondary-link {
    font-size: 0.875rem;
    font-weight: 600;
    color: #0891b2;
    text-decoration: none;
  }

  .secondary-link:hover {
    text-decoration: underline;
  }

  .disclosure {
    color: #64748b;
    font-size: 0.78rem;
    margin: 0.25rem 0 0;
  }
</style>
